	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Malagasy shrimp catches are in decline, but may soon be ‘eco-certified’</h1>

			
			<h4>
												31 March 2006
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> The Malagasy director of fisheries and marine resources said in an interview in February 2006 that the process leading to the eco-certification of Malagasy shrimp fisheries was well on the way. Recommendations have been made, and some of them are already being implemented, like the use of turtle-excluding devices (TEDs) by trawlers.</p><p> Eco-certified products command higher prices on markets, and the objective here is to maintain the supremacy of the Malagasy product in a context in which shrimps from other countries are tending to reduce prices on international markets. In this regard, the February <i>Globefish</i> report on the European shrimp market showed that the market shares of Malagasy shrimp in France, its main EU market, decreased by 17% between 2004 and 2005, to the benefit of products from Ecuador and Brazil.</p><p> The director of fisheries added that it is also essential to make considerable reductions in the fishing effort, given the declining shrimp catches. An article in <i>Mada Eco</i>, published in mid-March, noted that last year’s production was around 6000 tonnes, compared to a previous average of 8000 tonnes.</p><p>
<i>Mada Eco </i>further commented that lessons have been learned from last year’s EU veterinary-inspection mission. It reported that important efforts have been made, both by the private sector and the authorities, to ensure that Malagasy shrimp complies with EU sanitary regulations. The March 2006 issue of <i>Megapesca Fishfiles </i>stated that the veterinary mission made recommendations for the improvement of official controls by the Malagasy authorities. Consequently, short-term measures were introduced by the competent authority to withdraw approval from three factories, suspend approval from three more, and prohibit the supply of fish for export to EU from twelve freezer vessels.<br /> </p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p> Press article in <i> l'Express de Madagascar</i>, February 12th 2006</p><p>
<a href="http://www.lexpressmada.com/article.php?id=40582&amp;r=1&amp;d=2006-02-11" target="_self">http://www.lexpressmada.com/article.php?id=40582&amp;r=1&amp;d=2006-02-11</a> </p><p><i>Globefish</i> shrimp report, February 2006</p><p>
<a href="http://www.globefish.org/index.php?id=2703" target="_self">http://www.globefish.org/index.php?id=2703</a> </p><p><i>Mada Eco</i>, March 15th 2006</p><p>
<a href="http://www.wanadoo.mg/economieMadaEco.php?articleId=254971" target="_self">http://www.wanadoo.mg/economieMadaEco.php?articleId=254971</a> </p><p><i>Megapesca FishFiles</i>, March 2006</p><p>

<a href="http://www.megapesca.com/FishFiles Lite Monthly 2006/FFL200603.asp" target="_self">http://www.megapesca.com/FishFiles%20Lite%20Monthly%202006/FFL200603.asp</a> <br /> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> Malagasy shrimp is going through difficult times: catch declines of 25%, sanitary issues to address, and harsh competition from South American producers on the European market. Reactions by the state and the industry were necessary and most welcome, including: measures to be taken for the reduction of the fishing effort; improvement of the sanitary conditions and sanitary control chain; and the introduction of an eco-label on the shrimps.</p><p> An eco-label should certify that the fish is coming from a sustainably managed fishery, so its application to a resource that is being depleted by over-fishing is somewhat contradictory. Surely it is necessary to wait to see whether the measures implemented are sufficient to ensure sustainability of the stocks before applying an eco-labe &quot;lt is understandable that shrimp producers want to maintain the position of their products on international market, but it is equally important to clarify what the eco-label is certifying. Otherwise there is a risk of losing consumer confidence in eco-certified products, and this would be detrimental not only to the Malagasy shrimp but could rebound on other eco-certified fish products.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
